<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<quiz>
    <question>
        <prompt>In the long run Phillips Curve, what happens to the unemployment rate when inflation changes?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Unemployment increases with higher inflation</option>
            <option letter="b">Unemployment decreases with higher inflation</option>
            <option letter="c">Unemployment stays at the natural rate regardless of inflation</option>
            <option letter="d">Unemployment and inflation move in opposite directions</option>
        </options>
        <answer>c</answer>
        <explanation>The long-run Phillips Curve is vertical at the natural rate of unemployment, indicating that there is no permanent trade-off between inflation and unemployment. In the long run, the unemployment rate returns to its natural rate regardless of the inflation rate as expectations adjust.</explanation>
    </question>
</quiz>
